</e></d><d><e>status:operation:condition</e><e>condition</e><e>the query returns the sum of the bits in the condition register for the standard operation register group.</e></d><d><e>status:operation:enable</e><e>enable</e><e>the command enables bits in the enable register for the standard operation register group.</e></d><d><e>status:operation:event</e><e>event</e><e>the query returns the sum of the bits in the event register for the standard operation register group.</e></d><d><e>status:preset</e><e>preset</e><e>the command clears questionable data enable register and standard operation enable register.</e></d><d><e>status:questionable:condition</e><e>condition</e><e>the query returns the sum of the bits in the condition register for the questionable data register group.</e></d><d><e>status:questionable:enable</e><e>enable</e><e>the command enables bits in the enable register for the questionable data register group. </e></d><d><e>status:questionable:event</e><e>event</e><e>the query returns the event register for the questionable data register group. </e></d><d><e>system:acalibration:date</e><e>date</e><e>the query returns the date of the last autocalibration in the format yyyy,mm,dd. </e></d><d><e>system:acalibration:temperature</e><e>temperature</e><e>the query returns the temperature of the last autocalibration in °c.</e></d><d><e>system:acalibration:time</e><e>time</e><e>the query returns the time of the last autocalibration in the format hh,mm,ss.sss. </e></d><d><e>system:beeper:immediate</e><e>immediate</e><e>the command issues a single beep.</e></d><d><e>system:beeper:state</e><e>state</e><e>the command disables or enables the beep heard during continuity, diode, or probe hold measurements, or when an error is generated from the front panel or remote interface.</e></d><d><e>system:click:state</e><e>state</e><e>the command disables or enables the click heard when a front panel key or softkey is pressed.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:enable</e><e>enable</e><e>the command disables or enables the gpib, usb, or lan remote interface.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:gpib:address</e><e>address</e><e>the command assigns instrument's gpib (ieee-488) address, which is displayed at power-on. each device on the gpib interface must have a unique address.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:control</e><e>control</e><e>the query reads the initial control connection port number for sockets communications.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:dhcp</e><e>dhcp</e><e>the command disables or enables instrument's use of dhcp. </e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:dns</e><e>dns</e><e>the command assigns static ip addresses of domain name system (dns) servers. </e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:domain</e><e>domain</e><e>the query returns the domain name assigned to the instrument.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:gateway</e><e>gateway</e><e>the command assigns a default gateway for the instrument.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:hostname</e><e>hostname</e><e>the command assigns a hostname to the instrument.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:ipaddress</e><e>ipaddress</e><e>the command assigns a static internet protocol (ip) address for the instrument. </e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:mac</e><e>mac</e><e>the query returns the instrument's media access control (mac) address as an ascii string of 12 hexadecimal characters (0-9 and a-f) enclosed in quotation marks.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:smask</e><e>smask</e><e>the command assigns a subnet mask for the instrument to use in determining whether a client ip address is on the same local subnet.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:telnet:prompt</e><e>prompt</e><e>the command sets the command prompt seen when communicating with the instrument via telnet.
</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:telnet:wmessage</e><e>wmessage</e><e>the command sets welcome message seen when communicating with instrument via telnet.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:update</e><e>update</e><e>the command stores any changes made to the lan settings into non-volatile memory and restarts the lan driver with the updated settings.</e></d><d><e>system:communicate:lan:wins</e><e>wins</e><e>the command assigns the static ip addresses of the windows internet name system (wins) servers.</e></d><d><e>system:date</e><e>date</e><e>the command sets the date for the instrument's real-time clock.</e></d><d><e>system:error:next</e><e>next</e><e>the query reads and clears one error from the error queue. </e></d><d><e>system:help</e><e>help</e><e>the query returns a complete list of the instrument's scpi commands.</e></d><d><e>system:identify</e><e>identify</e><e>the command selects the manufacturer and model number returned by *idn?. </e></d><d><e>system:label</e><e>label</e><e>the command places a message in a large font on the bottom half of the instrument's front-panel display.</e></d><d><e>system:license:catalog</e><e>catalog</e><e>the query returns a comma separated list of installed, licensed options.</e></d><d><e>system:license:delete</e><e>delete</e><e>the command deletes a license and disables the associated functionality.</e></d><d><e>system:license:delete:all</e><e>all</e><e>the command deletes all licenses and disables the associated functionality.</e></d><d><e>system:license:description</e><e>description</e><e>the query returns a description of the specified option, regardless of whether it is currently licensed.</e></d><d><e>system:license:error</e><e>error</e><e>the query return the license installation error string.</e></d><d><e>system:license:error:count</e><e>count</e><e>the query returns the number of license errors generated by system:license:install.

</e></d><d><e>system:license:install</e><e>install</e><e>the command installs all licenses from a specified file or from all license files in the specified folder.</e></d><d><e>system:local</e><e>local</e><e>sets the instrument state to local, clears the remote display annunciator, and enables front-panel operation</e><e>system:local sets the instrument state to local, clears the remote display annunciator, and enables front-panel operation. parameter typical return (none) (none) set the instrument state to local: syst:loc </e></d><d><e>system:lock:name</e><e>name</e><e>the query returns the i/o interface in use by the querying computer.</e></d><d><e>system:lock:owner</e><e>owner</e><e>the query returns the i/o interface that currently has a lock.</e></d><d><e>system:lock:release</e><e>release</e><e>the command decrements the lock count by 1 and may release the i/o interface from which the command is executed.</e></d><d><e>system:lock:request</e><e>request</e><e>the query requests a lock of the current i/o interface. </e></d><d><e>system:preset</e><e>preset</e><e>the command resets the instrument for front-panel operation.</e></d><d><e>system:security:count</e><e>count</e><e>the query returns the instrument's security count.</e></d><d><e>system:security:immediate</e><e>immediate</e><e>the command sanitizes all user-accessible instrument memory except for the calibration constants and reboots the instrument.</e></d><d><e>system:temperature</e><e>temperature</e><e>the query returns the instrument's internal temperature in °c.</e></d><d><e>system:time</e><e>time</e><e>the command sets the time for the instrument's real-time clock.</e></d><d><e>system:uptime</e><e>uptime</e><e>the query returns the amount of time that the instrument has been running since the last power-on.</e></d><d><e>system:usb:host:enable</e><e>enable</e><e>the command disables or enables the front panel usb host port.</e></d><d><e>system:version</e><e>version</e><e>the query returns the version of scpi (standard commands for programmable instruments) that the instrument complies with.</e></d><d><e>system:wmessage</e><e>wmessage</e><e>the command displays a power-on message.</e></d><d><e>test:all</e><e>all</e><e>the query runs an instrument self-test and returns a pass/fail indication.</e></d><d><e>trigger:count</e><e>count</e><e>the command selects the number of triggers that will be accepted by the instrument before returning to the "idle" trigger state.</e></d><d><e>trigger:delay</e><e>delay</e><e>the command sets the delay between the trigger signal and the first measurement. </e></d><d><e>trigger:delay:auto</e><e>auto</e><e>the command disables or enables automatic trigger delay. </e></d><d><e>trigger:level</e><e>level</e><e>the command sets the level on which a trigger occurs when level triggering is enabled.</e></d><d><e>trigger:slope</e><e>slope</e><e>the command selects whether the instrument uses the rising edge (pos) or the falling edge (neg) of the trigger signal on the rear-panel ext trig bnc connector when external triggering is selected; or the rising or falling edge of the input signal when level triggering is selected </e></d><d><e>trigger:source</e><e>source</e><e>the command selects the trigger source for measurements.</e></d><d><e>unit:temperature</e><e>temperature</e><e>the command selects the units (°c, °f or kelvin) to be used for all temperature measurements.</e></d><d><e>*cal</e><e>*cal</e><e>peforms autocalibration (autocal) and returns the result.</e></d><d><e>*cls</e><e>*cls</e><e>clears the event registers in all register groups. </e></d><d><e>*ese</e><e>*ese</e><e>enables bits in the enable register for the standard event register group.</e></d><d><e>*esr</e><e>*esr</e><e>queries the event register for the standard event register group. </e></d><d><e>*idn</e><e>*idn</e><e>returns the instrument’s identification string.</e></d><d><e>*lrn</e><e>*lrn</e><e>returns an ascii string of all of the commands required to put the instrument into its current state.</e></d><d><e>*opc</e><e>*opc</e><e>sets "operation complete" (bit 0) in the standard event register at the completion of the current operation.
returns 1 to the output buffer after all pending commands complete. 

</e></d><d><e>*opt</e><e>*opt</e><e>returns a string identifying any installed options.</e></d><d><e>*psc</e><e>*psc</e><e>enables (1) or disables (0) the clearing of certain enable registers at power on.</e></d><d><e>*rcl</e><e>*rcl</e><e>this command recalls the instrument state from, the state file state_&lt;n&gt;.sta in the root folder of the internal flash file system.</e></d><d><e>*rst</e><e>*rst</e><e>resets instrument to factory default state.</e></d><d><e>*sav</e><e>*sav</e><e>stores the current instrument state to the state file state_&lt;n&gt;.sta in the root folder of the internal flash file system, where &lt;n&gt; is the number specified.</e></d><d><e>*sre</e><e>*sre</e><e>enables bits in the enable register for the status byte register group.</e></d><d><e>*stb</e><e>*stb</e><e>queries the condition register for the status byte register group and returns a decimal value equal to the binary-weighted sum of all bits set in the register.
</e></d><d><e>*trg</e><e>*trg</e><e>triggers the instrument if trigger:source bus is selected.</e></d><d><e>*tst</e><e>*tst</e><e>performs a basic self-test of the instrument and returns a pass/fail indication.</e></d><d><e>*wai</e><e>*wai</e><e>configures the instrument's output buffer to wait for all pending operations to complete before executing any additional commands over the interface.</e></d></a><a name="Transport"><d><e>defaulttimeout</e><e>defaulttimeout</e><e>defaulttimeout specifies the timeout, in milliseconds, for queries issued to this instrument.

a timeout will occur if there is no response from the instrument within the specified duration.

a value of -1 is used to specify no timeout.
</e></d><d><e>errorquerybehavior</e><e>errorquerybehavior</e><e>errorquerybehavior specifies whether command expert automatically retrieves errors from the instrument's scpi error queue by sending syst:err? queries. command expert displays errors retrieved from the scpi error queue in the results column of the sequence pane.

the supported values for errorquerybehavior are:

     none - syst:err? queries will not be automatically sent.

     errorquerypercommand - a :syst:err? query will be sent after each command, and after each query that times out.

     errorquerypercommandandquery - a :syst:err? query will be sent after each command and after each query.
</e></d><d><e>opcbehavior</e><e>opcbehavior</e><e>opcbehavior specifies whether command expert automatically sends a *opc? query after each command.

the supported values for opcbehavior are:

     none - *opc? queries will not be automatically sent to the instrument.

     opcpercommand - an *opc? query will be sent after every command, and no further commands or queries will be sent until the *opc? returns.
</e></d><d><e>omitdefaultkeywords</e><e>omitdefaultkeywords</e><e>omitdefaultkeywords specifies whether to omit default keywords when sending scpi commands.</e></d><d><e>useshortformkeywords</e><e>useshortformkeywords</e><e>useshortformkeywords specifies whether to use the short form of spci keywords when sending scpi commands.</e></d><d><e>ignorederrors</e><e>ignorederrors</e><e>ignorederrors is a string that specifies the list of scpi error codes that will be ignored during execution.

for example, setting ignorederrors to the string "1:100,301:400" specifies that error codes from 1 to 100 inclusive and 301 to 400 inclusive will be ignored.

when setting ignorederrors, the input string should contain a list of zero or more items, separated by commas. each item is either an integer, or a range of the form x:y where x and y are integers. the integers can be positive, 0, or negative.</e></d><d><e>addtoignorederrors</e><e>addtoignorederrors</e><e>addtoignorederrors adds the specified error codes to ignorederrors (the list of scpi error codes ignored during execution).

for example, invoking addtoignorederrors with the string "1:100,301:400" will add the error codes from 1 to 100 inclusive and 301 to 400 inclusive.

when invoking addtoignorederrors, the input string should contain a list of zero or more items, separated by commas. each item is either an integer, or a range of the form x:y where x and y are integers. the integers can be positive, 0, or negative.</e></d><d><e>removefromignorederrors</e><e>removefromignorederrors</e><e>removefromignorederrors removes the specified error codes from ignorederrors (the list of scpi error codes ignored during execution).

for example, invoking removefromignorederrors with the string "1:100,301:400" will remove the error codes from 1 to 100 inclusive and 301 to 400 inclusive.

when invoking removefromignorederrors, the input string should contain a list of zero or more items, separated by commas. each item is either an integer, or a range of the form x:y where x and y are integers. the integers can be positive, 0, or negative.</e></d><d><e>command</e><e>command</e><e>sends a scpi command that does not return a response from the instrument.  use the transport resource query if the instrument returns a response.</e></d><d><e>query</e><e>query</e><e>sends a scpi query string directly to the instrument and returns the result.</e></d><d><e>commandbatching</e><e>commandbatching</e><e>commandbatching specifies scpi command batching behavior.
</e></d><d><e>sendbatchedcommands</e><e>sendbatchedcommands</e><e>sendbatchedcommands sends any commands that are currently batched.
